segments.text: Yeah, we're picking up on it.
This is January 27, I believe, Wednesday, and in the living room on 1016 Guadalupe and College Station, talking to Bill Lay, and now going to stop and see if the machine is working.
Bill, as a starter, to introduce you to any

reader or listener in the future would you give a brief biographical summary up to the point that you go to work for A&M where did you grow up high school college other experience before you came to work at A&M actually I guess we call Valley Mills Texas home that's where my
grandparents both lived and where I was born.
I lived there until about we were so about six years.
I was about six years old, about 1936.
And my dad took a job at that time, which was right in the middle of depression.
And Gatesville, Texas working with state training school over there was a school for boys which had had a game.
So he worked over there taught paper hanging and painting to the boys and help with some of the maintenance there.
And then about 19
41, he quit that job and we moved to Pasadena, Texas, which was a long way from Gatesville, Texas.
I spent the remainder of my youth in Pasadena and graduated from Pasadena High School in 1949.
And at that time, one of my

Actually, one of our former landlords was a strong Aggie supporter, and he'd always encourage me to come to Texas A&M, and I enrolled at Texas A&M in 1949 at what was then called the Annex, which is the old Bryan Air Force Base, which is now called Riverside Campus.
As many of you will know, the A&M system used that for freshmen for four years, I believe.
We were the last class there and it was rather spartan existence.

I can remember my mother telling me about that she dropped me off at this tar paper buildings that they had out there at that time, turned the corner and was crying all the way home that she had left me in such an ungodly place as this.
But we survived the annex and I came back onto the campus the next year and I graduated from Texas A&M in 1954.
At that time, I took ROTC while I was at A&M.
At that time, there were not enough commissions for everyone.
So they gave me a National Guard assignment and said I could come on duty, active duty, if I wanted to as a sergeant, I believe, in the National Guard.
And I told them no thank you at that time.
So I went back and taught a year at school and then passed it in Texas.
And sometime during the year, they found some commission, a commission in the National Guard for me as a second lieutenant, and then called me to active duty in 1954 in the summer.
And of all places to send me, they sent me back to Bryan Air Force Base.
And I thought I was going to begin and end my career at Bryan Air Force Base.

Sometime again by the end of the summer I think they found some not regular commission but reserve commissions and I was given a reserve commission in the Air Force as a second lieutenant and we stayed here until 1958 when they closed the base.
In the meantime I had met a young lady and got married and we had a child while I was still stationed here and we went from
here to England, spent three years in England, came back and spent about two years in San Antonio at the Security Service headquarters.
And I was not particularly enamored with being in the Air Force, although I had a good career.
But I heard President Kennedy at that time say, that's not what your country can do for you, but what you can do for your country.
And

I felt I would be better off in the public school, so I resigned my commission, which was a regular commission at that time, and a captaincy in the Air Force, and went back to teaching school in Pasadena, of all places.
They had asked me to come back there, and I thought I was going to starve to death for a few years, but eventually we got on our feet, and I
I began to take courses in school administration, and I took some work at the University of Texas during the summer of 1963, which was an intern-type program they had for prospective administrators.
And went back and taught a couple of years after that, and then went full-time to the University of Texas in 1965 and finished up a master's and doctorate there.
I was working for the Austin Public Schools during that period of time, working as an assistant principal, a principal, and a dean of men at three different times.
And when I finished my doctorate, the Austin Public Schools didn't at that time have a specific position in administration for me other than an assistant principal.
And I'd had enough of being an assistant principal.

and I called my friend Ed Cooper who I had seen in the issues of Aggieland was working here at the university and although we hadn't been in contact with each other for quite some time you know Aggies and Aggies in the band especially maintain some kind of relationship and I called him and asked him if he knew of any positions in school administration department or the
in the school administration department here, they might be open, thinking I might get a teaching job or something like this.
And he said no, but he was director of admissions, and he was going to work for Dr. Williams, and his position was open.
I wanted to come and interview for him.

Well, at that time I didn't know what the Director of Admissions was, did, or anything else, but it was a chance for a job and it was a Texan A&M, so I said, sure, I'll come over and talk to him about it, having no idea what to expect or anything else.
And I came over and interviewed with Dean Heaton and probably some other members of his staff, and I'm not really sure who I did talk to.
When was that?
This was in 1971.
Spring, fall?
In the spring of 71.
And I interviewed, had a nice visit, went back home, and I thought, well, that's the last of that.
Went ahead and carried on with the business at Crockett High School where I was employed.
And probably two weeks later, I got another call from someone, and I'm not sure whether it was Dean Heaton or others from Ed,
asked if I'd come back over for another interview.
Well, I thought, well, they've narrowed it down to two or three people, and they want to do some more interviewing.
So I jumped in the car and came back over here, and I think it was probably a Saturday morning, although I'm not sure what day of the week it was.
And after talking a little while, he says, would you like to, Dr. Byers would like to talk to you.
Vice President Hurst.
Vice President, or he wasn't pro, he was Vice President Horst Byers, I believe.
And I says, yes.
So I went in and talked to Dr. Byers, and he says, well, we'd like to offer you a job.
And I swallowed kind of hard because I hadn't even thought about it.
And we talked a little bit more, and the terms were certainly better than what I was making, and it was kind of what I was hoping to
make as far as any move that we were looking at and I immediately called my wife and told her to start packing the bags that we were coming over here and that's kind of the way I got here.
I started in June of 1971.
What was that opening salary?
Opening salary
I want to say it's 17-5.
I think that's what it was.
And this is 60, I mean 71.
And the enrollment, though, I never forget.
The enrollment was, give or take a few, 14,700.
I do remember that.
That's where we started.
Okay.
Describe the staff of admissions and records at that time.
Who were the key people?
Where were you located and so forth?
Right now, that seems like ancient history, but I'll do my best.
At that time, the office was located in the Koch building.
We were on the second floor.
The admissions part was on the second floor, to put it differently.
And the other half was occupied by the graduate college, I believe, and the vice president, I think, as I recall.
We had the, I guess it's the north half.
The registrar's part was directly under us at that time.
In underground, in the basement.
And on the basement, that's correct.
Dean Heaton was the dean.
Ray Perryman was an associate dean.
Bob Lacy was the registrar.
I think Don was there at that time.
Don Carter.
Don Carter was there at that time, I believe.
Carolyn Mitchell was in the admissions office.
Leona Dean was in the admissions office.
Carolyn, Ms. Mitchell took care of the transfer student area.
Ms. Dean was taking care of the graduate admission area.
And Homer Smith was taking care of the undergraduate area.
Describe those people as professional associates, beginning with Mr. Heaton.
Tell me about Lloyd Heaton.
The thing I regret most about Mr. Heaton, knowing Mr. Heaton, was the fact that I didn't know him very long.
Mr. Heaton retired several years after I got there.
And I didn't work as closely with Mr. Heaton as I would have if I had been there over a period of time because we were working like crazy trying to keep up.
Mr. Heaton was very precise, as I recall, very nice to me as far as I was concerned.
I'll always have a fond spot in my heart for him for hiring me to the job, which I really thought I couldn't do any better anywhere.
It turned out, I think, that was true.
I certainly enjoyed my relationship there at all times.
It's hard to remember a whole lot about Mr. Heaton because I just didn't work with him that long.
Do you remember his key likes and dislikes?
Not really.
I really don't.
That part I didn't get to know about.
I knew he was very precise, I think.
He was, I think, had an extremely high moral character.
But he believed in, he believed in very strongly, I think.
knowing a lot of the little intricacies about how he did things and I really don't remember those things it's been too long.
What about then Perryman?
Ray uh what was his responsibility and his way of doing it?
Ray was his assistant registrar I think and at that time as I recall he I know he had charge of the graduation part of it I'm sure he had charge of the certain
reviews of certain records and keeping the records and things like this, again, didn't associate with Ray very much at all.
Again, he retired three or four years after I got there as well.
And as you know, like I say, during that time admissions was just booming.
When I walked in, there were, we had papers stacked all over the place.
And because everything was done by hand, we, applications came in,
piece by piece.
We were getting more applications than we could handle.
At that time, we still admitted everybody who qualified.
We enrolled everybody who showed up at the door, so to speak.
But the handling of the applications, we had very little electronic
equipment to handle it, as I recall.
It used to be that the problem was trying to get all the pieces of record together so that you could review an application.
I never forget down in the basement itself.
I think the number was 62, but I could be off.
We had 62 four drawer filing cabinets down in the basement, which contained the records of applicants.
Those are who people who had been here.
Could we still kept the the paper file for years afterwards, which get that they knew just
huge area down in the basement where he kept records and everything.
Now this and these files were both those who had been admitted and those who had not been admitted.
Yes, actually those and those who had enrolled too we kept those for a period of time.
We kept those who had applied and didn't get admitted for a period of time and we eventually destroyed them.
But once they were had applied and been admitted then we kept those records as I recall forever.
We eventually got into the process of microfilming and it cut down on the
the space that we needed and it made it much easier to find as far as that goes.
We had a pretty good paper mill going there.
Your staff as Director of Admissions, at that point, who were the people that worked directly with you?
He actually came in as Director of Admissions.
Homer Smith was in charge of Undergraduate Admissions.
Carolyn Mitchell, the Transfer Admissions, and Louina Dean in Graduate Admissions.
What's Dean's first name?
Leona.
Leona, spell it.
L-A, capital U-N-A.
And she and Ms. Mitchell had been there for a long time.
many stories about Carolyn Mitchell and her operation there, but she was very good at what she did.
She knew how to do it and she was very fair with everyone in that sense.
Can you share some of those stories?
Probably not.
But she, I think we used to, Ms. Mitchell
She tried to keep everything in order, and she was working, doing a number of jobs.
Ms. Mitchell took care of the transfer admissions.
She took care of the certifying of athletes, and there were one or two other jobs that she had that when she retired, we hired probably three other people to replace her.
But Ms. Mitchell, when the applicants came in, she would be, not only did she do the admission of the athletes,
She also did the evaluation of the transfer work, which in itself is a job, which now is split out.
The admissions part is handled for one thing, and then we have another complete section handling the evaluation of the credit that's being transferred now.
But she would always, when she'd be working on things, when things would be ready, it would go to the bottom of the pile, and she would work her way down.
Stuff didn't get on the top of the pile.
I always was amazed at how she kept things in order, you know.
Or she was working on three different things.
She'd work a while on this and she'd work a while on something else.
I will share one thing with you.
I don't think she would mind hearing this.
In certifying the athletes, because it was just as much a problem then as it is now, if not more in the sense that you didn't have as much...
much help and he didn't have as good a way of keeping track of things as we do now.
But I do remember she said that in Ed Hargett's case that she cheated on Ed Hargett in reporting
She says, Ed Hargett had a 4.01 because of the fact at that time we gave credit for PE, but no hours.
And therefore, you can have better than a 4.0.
And she said she knew nobody believed he had a 4.01, so she just rounded it to a 4.0.
Oh, now that's a good story.
Because I had Ed in class, and I remember what a good student he was in my history class.
All right, when you began, did anybody
give you advice and counsel in how to do the task?
What guidance, what advice did you get to begin?
I'm sure that I was given some.
It's hard to remember right now.
I do remember that the person who was in charge of the freshman admissions
had some leave coming and my coming there coincided with the amount of leave he had to take before he was going to retire or to leave the university.
And soon after I got there with a brief amount of instructions, he took his leave and I was in charge at that time.

and didn't have the person in charge of the freshman admissions and I was trying to hire a person to be in charge of the freshman admissions during the summer while I was trying to learn the job and we were trying to keep applications flowing at that time.
So it got really hectic that first summer.
Did anybody tell you any absolute do's and don'ts?
It's hard to learn.
I'm sure we were given instructions, guidance as to what the admission criteria was and I'm sure that we went by that.
I don't recall
being given instruction as particular ways of having to do things.
Actually, I was trying to learn the process of doing things, which is what I was trying to do.
Trying to learn how to check to see the student had the proper admission.
Trying to, I'm sure at that time, although I don't remember the specifics, dealing with concerns of people who wanted to get their students admitted and those kinds of procedures.
Other than the fact that it was a whirl of paper and that I was trying to hire a new assistant director of admissions, it's kind of a blur as to what happened at that time.
In those early years, for you early years, an application included a transcript
And what else?
The high school, they had to furnish us a transcript which would reflect certain credits which they had to have for admission.
And then we based it on a... Was there any other pieces of paper?
A standardized test, an SAT or the ACT.
We were already requiring that of all?
As I recall, there was a minimum that you had to have.
I'd have to go back and check it.
quite some time, but I was thinking that we had to have the high school graduate a certain score on the SAT and a certain class rank on that.
You don't remember what those were?
I really don't remember what they were.
I know we increased it in probably, Dr. Williams was there in 1976.
That sounded like a good year.

Because I remember that in questioning the testing office, they'd come up with a cut-off figure, as I recall, and they'd made certain studies on what levels they thought were appropriate and what weren't.
I think that it was 800 in the top half,
I'm not sure on the thing.
900 in the third quarter and 1,000 in the fourth.
That was a criteria at some time, and I think that's when we came in in 1971.
That's what we used.
Give me some examples of disappointed applicants or disappointed parents of applicants.
What were some of the experiences you had?
Any time.
about admissions.
There had to be phone calls, letters.
Oh, gosh, there's, I'm sure there are literally hundreds of them.
It's easier, you're going to interview Ed, so I'll let you talk to Ed about one of his experiences about the big,
plumber or pipe fitter or whoever it was that wanted to talk to Cooper.
But most of the time, we tried to deal with the students from the standpoint of that we're not denying you admission to Texas A&M.
We're trying to provide you a way to be a graduate of Texas A&M.
And in dealing with them, you didn't make everybody happy.
But I'm not sure we made anybody extremely mad at us on the thing.
We hoped that we could say, although you don't meet what we consider the proper requirements, there are certain things you can do.
And at that time, we had the summer provisional program, as you may recall.
And it gave us an out, in a sense.
And I say an out.
It gave the student another way to prove that they had
ability, the determination, whatever it may take to come in and
be successful at Texas A&M.
And therefore we never quote denied anybody the right to come to Texas A&M in that sense.
We said right now you don't meet the requirements.
If you want to come to the summer provisional program you can come and meet the requirements of the provisional program and then you can enter on in in the fall.
Could anybody go in the summer?
At that time anybody could come in and enter the summer too.
Now I'm realizing that
It was impossible for some to come because of work situations and distance and other things, but otherwise the program was open to anybody who wanted to come.
What did it take in the summer, what courses and grades, to survive for the fall?
I want to say at that time that it took 12 hours and a 2.5 average or
I believe.
Were there any courses that had to be included?
Early on, I don't think there were.
We did go to where we had to because we found that a lot of students were, some were taking it very difficult.

Some advisors, let me put it this way, would assign a very difficult program for some, and some of them would provide, give them some what we considered easier courses, and they didn't think it was really fair to the students, nor did it give you
the basis on which they might be successful.
Early on, when I say early on, in 71 when I went there, I think they could take any 12 hours.
It takes six hours a summer school session and had to, and I believe the figure, I don't know whether it's the 2.5 or the 3.
3 sounds a little high to me.
I think it's a 2.5.
And eventually, maybe it's forgetful, but I think English and math

one of each was included eventually there were some core courses that had to be and then there were some others that could be added in from a select group but we we got away from just a wide open selection of courses so uh and as i recall about half of the students who tried it in the summer made it
Then, of that half that survived in the summer, what is your recollection of how well they did toward graduation?
Again, I want to say about half of those made it on to graduation.
So they didn't do quite as well as those that were fully admitted to begin with?
I don't think they did quite as well, but a lot of them came through that route and did graduate.
And it was hard to tell because some of those who didn't make it then eventually may have come back as transfer students too.
In those early days was there any particular geographic pattern to our enrollment sources?
Where did the students come from?
Well I think for the most part
They came from the larger metropolitan areas, there were just more students there.
But there were, again, at one time I can remember, seemed like maybe two or three counties didn't have anybody from it.
But most counties in the state of Texas would have one, two, three, or more students come from there.
They were occasionally, they were, there were always a certain few, I'm not sure how many people lived in the county, but there were,
It did pretty well spread all over the state, but again, you had more students coming from Harris County, Bexar County, and Dallas and Tarrant Counties.
Don't I remember Harris maybe 20-25% of the student body?
Probably so.
Harris was the biggest.
It always showed up in the figures that you had a lot from Brazos County.
But I think that's because a lot of them listed this as their home.
Therefore, it showed up at more students here.
There just weren't that many students to come from Bassett County, although it was maybe third or fourth in numbers as far as total enrollment was concerned.
All right.
Still on admissions, y'all would get these applications.
And as far as you recall, early on, what was the turnaround time in notification?
Do you remember in those pre-
Computer days?
I don't remember.
It wasn't very good, I'm sure, though.
The time we got them in, got the things together and everything, I don't remember the procedure we used as far as getting the information back to them, whether it had been admitted or not.
But pretty slow as far as they were concerned, I would imagine.
Do you remember any unusual situations where a student sent their seventh semester
transcript with their application, but then when their eighth semester official transcript came in, that it had changed?

Yeah, we had those occasions, and admission was conditioned on the fact that they, well, let's see, it was conditioned on the fact that they graduated from high school, so we had to, not only did we have to

verify that they had the proper information based on seven and then we did it was based on seven semesters uh we had to go back then and get a report from the high school showing that they did graduate and we had a look you know some that didn't that were admitted but didn't graduate and therefore they were not eligible to come on the thing i don't recall
I don't know that we even checked to see if they maintained a class rank.
I think if they were admitted based on being in the top half, if they dropped to the third quarter, I don't think we paid any attention to it at that time.
But we did pay it too close to the fact that they were a high school graduate because that was part of the admission requirement.
And that was a real problem trying to get information in from counselors, schools, between June and
middle of August when they started coming for their summer conferences.
All right, now Ed Cooper would replace Mr. Heaton.
Right, Ed replaced Mr. Heaton when he retired.
In the early 70s.
In 73 possibly, something like that.
All right, describe Ed then as the Dean of Admissions and Records.
What was his normal work style and so forth?
I enjoyed working with Ed.
I never did work before Ed.
I worked with him.
Of course, having been a classmate of Ed, we had known each other for years on the thing.
Ed was the dean and he coordinated the work of the admissions and the registrar.
And although I can't speak for Bob,
It was an excellent person to work for in the sense that he assumed I knew what I was supposed to do, and he let me do it.
